Europe
------
[1] Spain (Asturias)
Date: Wed 10 Aug 2011
Source: La Voz de Asturias [in Spanish, machine translation, abridged
& edited]


The measles outbreak detected in Asturias in May 2011, after more than
a decade with no positive diagnoses, has now been contained. The
health authorities anticipate that any new cases will be confined to
people arriving in Asturias from regions with active measles
transmission, although further patient-related cases within the
Principality of Asturias cannot be entirely ruled out.

Despite this favourable situation, the administration does not want to
relax its precautions, insisting that vaccination is the best means of
protection of the community and that the best way to keep the disease
under control is continued surveillance and early diagnosis.

In the 4 months of the outbreak of measles in Asturias, 36 cases were
reported initially, but subsequently 13 were discounted. Of the 23
positives, one is still under investigation; another has been
confirmed by an epidemiological link to a previous patient; 2 have
appropriate symptoms but lack clinical samples, while the remaining 13
have been confirmed unambiguously.

15 of the patients were male, and 8 were female. The 1st case was
detected on 4 May 2011 and subsequently the rate of appearance of new
patients with symptoms was rapid. By the end of June 2011, that is in
less than 2 months, it was suspected that the outbreak had involved 25
patients. The Health authorities now report that the spread of the
virus in Asturias in the last month "has been almost nil," leading to
the conclusion that the outbreak is now under control.

Measles is a highly contagious viral disease, against which the
Asturian population have vaccinated for more than 30 years. Despite
the high vaccination coverage, the emergence of new foci from a single
infected patient can occur, especially in infants who, because of
their young age, may not have been vaccinated. The health authorities
believe that all those born before 1978 in Asturias are protected,
since laboratory tests have confirmed their immunity. Others will have
received 2 doses of MMR vaccine.

So why has this outbreak occurred? In fact, 5 of the victims were
children under 15 months and, therefore, had not yet been vaccinated.
Three others were children between 16 months and 3 years and had
received only a single dose of vaccine at that stage. Four were
persons born prior to 1982 and were unvaccinated. Of the remaining 11,
aged between 3 and 30, 4 were found not to have been vaccinated;
another was of unknown immune status; one had received only one dose,
and the remainder were infected despite being vaccinated.

The region of Asturias with the highest incidence was Mieres. The
initial case was a teenager who had spent Easter in Madrid and had
exposed his brother to the infection. Both went to ER Alvarez-Buylla
Hospital, where they in turn infected other patients.

[byline: Susan D Oviedo Machargo]

