[4] Australia (South Australia)
Date: Thu 12 Aug 2011
Source: Adelaide Now [edited]
http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/south-australia/new-measles-cases-prompt-warning/story-e6frea83-1226113247592


Two new measles cases have been detected in Adelaide, and the health
authorities are urging the public to update their vaccinations. South
Australia (SA) Health issued an alert today [12 Aug 2011], saying the
new cases were linked to a man with measles who flew from Dubai to
Adelaide on 8 Jul 2011. One of the new cases worked 2 shifts at a
Burnside shoe shop and spent a night in Hindley Street bars while
infectious.

SA Health chief medical officer Professor Paddy Phillips said measles
was highly contagious and people who had been in those areas should be
alert for symptoms. "SA Health is currently contacting those who may
have spent time with either of these people to provide information and
advice about prevention measures," he said.

"One visited several public places during their infectious period,
including Va Bene at the Burnside Village on Fri 22 Jul 2011 from 11am
to 5:30pm and on Sat 23 Jul 2011 from 10am to 5pm. "The same person
was also in the Hindley Street precinct, including the Red Square Bar
and Lounge and the Rosemont Hotel between 11:50pm on Sat 23 Jul 2011
to 4am on Sun 24 Jul 2011. The latest cases were in "close contact"
with the original case but did not contract the virus on the flight to
Adelaide.

Symptoms usually begin with fever, cough, runny nose, and sore eyes,
followed by a rash which begins on the head and then spreads down the
body. Measles is spread through the air and is highly contagious among
people who are not fully immunised. "Although usually not severe,
complications of measles can include pneumonia, brain damage and
death, and anyone with suspected symptoms should seek advice from
their local doctor," Professor Phillips said. "It is very important,
however, that people phone their GP ahead of any visit and mention why
they are attending, so that precautions can be taken to avoid
spreading disease to others." An alert has been issued to general
practitioners advising them of these cases.

Immunisation provides the best protection against measles. Two doses
of measles-containing vaccine are strongly recommended for anyone born
after 1965. People in this age group are encouraged to check their
vaccination records and request the vaccine if there is no record of 2
doses of measles vaccine.

SA has recorded 3 measles cases in 2011, compared with one in 2010. A
fact sheet about measles can be found on SA Health's website at
http://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au.

[byline: Jill Pengelley]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[Part [8] in Measles update 2011 (23) 20110717.2169 reported an alert
issued by SA Health concerning the arrival in Australia of a
measles-infected passenger from Dubai. Today's (12 Aug 2011) report
indicates that none of the passengers on that flight are known to have
contracted measles. However, 2 people in contact with the index case
after his arrival have developed measles, and there is now a risk of
spread of the infection in Adelaide.

