[5] Australia (New South Wales)
Date: Fri 12 Aug 2011
Source: PhilSTAR.com, Xinhua report [edited]
http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?articleId=715992&publicationSubCategoryId=200


The Australian New South Wales (NSW) health authorities on Friday [12
Aug 2011] issued a measles vaccination reminder following a spike in
the number of cases in Sydney.

NSW director of health protection Dr Jeremy McAnulty said 7 cases of
measles have been reported in NSW since the start of July 2011. "All 7
cases were acquired in the Sydney metropolitan region, where several
adults in their 20s and 30s were infected," he said.

The rash of cases has puzzled doctors who are unable to pinpoint
precisely the source of the current outbreak. "This is a little
unusual as most cases in NSW tend to be seen in unvaccinated or
partially vaccinated people who have recently returned from travel
overseas. The original source of their infection is unknown," McAnulty
said.

Some 56 measles cases have been recorded in NSW so far in 2011. That
compares to a total of 26 in 2010, 19 in 2009, 39 in 2008, and 3 in
2007.

NSW Health says measles is a serious infection that can lead to severe
complications. "Anyone with measles is extremely infectious, and just
one person with the infection can pass it on to many others," McAnulty
said. NSW Health is urging people to get vaccinated against measles as
soon as possible.

People with measles tend to be unwell and develop fever, cough, runny
nose, sore eyes. A rash starts a few days later, starting on the face
and spreads down the body. Although 90 to 95 per cent of NSW's
population is vaccinated against measles, NSW Health warns that many
people in their 20s, 30s, and early 40s are still vulnerable to
measles because they only ever received one measles mumps and rubella
(MMR) vaccine dose in childhood. The MMR vaccine is safe and effective
and provides long lasting protection if 2 doses are given, NSW Health
says.

